You are desining a tool analyze the structural integrity of wooden planks. Each plank has specific length, and you need to determine
if three planks can form a trianle frame. the goal is to find the maximum perimeter of such triangle frame,if
possible.
A set of three can a valid triangle frame if they statify the triangle in equality

* the sum of the lengths of any two planks must be greater than the length of the third plank
if no such combinations exists, it mean a triangle frame cannot be formed, and the result should be -1

Example 1:

 INPUT

n = 5
plankslength= [10, 15, 5, 20,25]

OUTPUT

60

Example 2:

INPUT 
 n = 4
plankslength= [3, 1, 2, 1]

OUTPUT
-1


Maximum Triangle Perimeter

Intuition
A triangle can be formed only if the sum of any two sides is greater than the third side, so we mainly check the largest side against the other two sides.

To maximize the perimeter, it is better to try larger numbers first because larger sides will give a bigger perimeter.

By sorting the Array in decreasing order, the largest elements appear first, making it easier to check the biggest possible triangle combinations.

Once we find the first valid triple that satisfies the triangle condition, it automatically gives the maximum possible perimeter.

Approach
Sort the Array in descending order so that the largest side lengths are checked first.

Traverse the Array and examine every group of three consecutive elements.

For each group, check if the largest side is smaller than the sum of the other two sides to satisfy the triangle condition.

If the condition holds, return the sum of the three sides as the maximum triangle perimeter; if no such triplet exists after checking all possibilities, return -1.


Pseudo Code

findMaxTrianglePerimeter(plankLengths) {
    /* Get the number of elements in the Array */
    n ← size of plankLengths
    /* Sort the Array in descending order so that larger sides are checked first */
    sort plankLengths in decreasing order
    /* Traverse the Array and check every group of three consecutive elements */
    for (i from 0 to n - 3) {
        /* Check the triangle inequality condition */
        /* A triangle is valid if the largest side is smaller than the sum of the other two */
        if plankLengths[i] < plankLengths[i + 1] + plankLengths[i + 2] {
            /* If a valid triangle is found, return its perimeter */
            return plankLengths[i] + plankLengths[i + 1] + plankLengths[i + 2]
        }
    }
    /* If no valid triangle can be formed, return -1 */
    return -1
}



code in C++

#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution {
  public:
    int findMaxTrianglePerimeter(vector<int> &plankLengths) {
        int n = plankLengths.size();
        sort(plankLengths.rbegin(), plankLengths.rend());
        for (int i = 0; i <= n - 3; i++) {
            if (plankLengths[i] < plankLengths[i + 1] + plankLengths[i + 2]) {
                return plankLengths[i] + plankLengths[i + 1] + plankLengths[i + 2];
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
};

